# Clean Code and Small Functions

## Core Principles

- Prefer small functions that do one thing well.
- Keep functions easy to scan and reason about.
- Use clear, intention-revealing names for variables and functions.
- Avoid deeply nested conditionals; use early returns when possible.
- Remove dead code and avoid commented-out code blocks.

## Function Guidelines

- Aim for short functions (roughly 5-20 lines when practical).
- Extract repeated logic into helper functions.
- Pass only the data a function needs.
- Keep side effects explicit and localized.

## Naming

- Use descriptive names (`calculateTotalPrice`) over vague ones (`doStuff`).
- Boolean names should read like questions (`isLoading`, `hasAccess`).
- Avoid abbreviations unless they are standard and obvious.

## Example

```javascript
// ❌ Too much responsibility in one function
function submitForm(data) {
  if (!data.email) return;
  const email = data.email.trim().toLowerCase();
  if (!email.includes("@")) return;
  const payload = { ...data, email };
  localStorage.setItem("draft", JSON.stringify(payload));
  return fetch("/api/submit", {
    method: "POST",
    headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
    body: JSON.stringify(payload),
  });
}

// ✅ Smaller functions with clear intent
function normalizeEmail(email) {
  return email.trim().toLowerCase();
}

function isValidEmail(email) {
  return email.includes("@");
}

async function submitForm(data) {
  if (!data.email) return;
  const email = normalizeEmail(data.email);
  if (!isValidEmail(email)) return;

  const payload = { ...data, email };
  localStorage.setItem("draft", JSON.stringify(payload));
  return fetch("/api/submit", {
    method: "POST",
    headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
    body: JSON.stringify(payload),
  });
}
```
